# The Arc of Labor Organization: From Factory Floor to Algorithm

**A Research Analysis of the Evolution, Dissolution, and Future Trajectory of Factory Worker Labor Organizations in the Age of Artificial Intelligence**

-----

## The Incident: April 6, 2026, Troutdale, Oregon

The facts are grim and well-documented. On April 6, a 46-year-old tote runner collapsed on the second floor of Amazon’s PDX9 fulfillment center in Troutdale, Oregon.[^1] A woman rushed to perform CPR. An employee identified by the pseudonym Sam, who is CPR-certified, asked her supervisor if she could help. The supervisor replied: “It has to be management or safety team. Please get back to work.”[^1] Sam pressed further, and the supervisor — with tears in her own eyes — nudged Sam away, saying to turn around and not look.[^1]

Workers continued picking items and loading trucks as the man lay on the floor for over an hour.[^1] Supervisors did not tell all employees someone had died. That evening, workers received a text: report to work as usual the next day.[^1]

What makes this incident structurally important — not just morally horrifying — is what it crystallizes about a century of labor history collapsing into a single moment: the supervisor crying while enforcing the protocol. The human being trapped inside the system, executing the algorithm. That is the image of where we are.

-----

## Part I: The Rise — How Factory Workers Built Power (1790s–1955)

Labor organizing in America predates the country’s industrialization. The earliest recorded strike occurred in 1768 when New York journeymen tailors protested a wage reduction. The formation of the Federal Society of Journeymen Cordwainers in Philadelphia in 1794 marks the beginning of sustained trade union organization.[^2]

For over a century, organizing was dangerous and largely illegal. Employers fought union organizing with violence, and courts typically sided with employers, treating unions as illegal conspiracies to raise wages.[^3]

The breakthrough came during the Great Depression. In the 1930s, workers reacted to devastating conditions with a massive wave of organizing and strikes, and by 1935, the Roosevelt administration passed the National Labor Relations Act (NLRA), establishing a legal framework for workers to join unions, hold elections, and bargain contracts.[^3] This was followed by the explosive growth of the CIO and industrial unionism. Union membership grew from 2.8 million in 1933 to 8.4 million in 1941, reaching 14 million by 1945 — about 36% of the workforce.[^4] By the mid-1950s, around a third of the American labor force was unionized.[^4]

-----

## Part II: The Dismantling (1947–2020)

The decline began almost immediately after labor’s peak — and critically, the Economic Policy Institute’s research demonstrates it was not primarily caused by automation or globalization.

### Taft-Hartley (1947)

The act placed significant restrictions on unions, prohibited secondary boycotts, opened the door to right-to-work laws, and required union leaders to sign anti-Communist affidavits.[^5] This landed during “Operation Dixie,” the campaign to organize the South. Anti-union leaders in the South used accusations of communism and the threat of desegregation to crush the campaign. It failed — and the Southern textile industry remained un-unionized.[^5] That failure echoes through the present: Amazon’s most aggressive union defeats have occurred in right-to-work states in the South.

### Structural Legal Decay

While 86% of workers who chose a union were able to win a first contract in the 1950s, that share declined to less than 70% in the 1970s, and by the 1990s it was down to 56%.[^6] The law increasingly allowed employers to delay, obstruct, and retaliate with minimal consequences.

### The Reagan Fracture (1981)

President Reagan broke the PATCO strike in 1981, dealing a major blow to organized labor.[^4] Between 1975 and 1985, union membership fell by 5 million. In manufacturing, the unionized portion of the labor force dropped below 25%.[^2]

### Globalization and Deregulation

The opening of overseas markets increased competition in highly organized industries. Outsourcing emerged as a popular practice. Deregulation of industries like trucking placed organized labor at a disadvantage as new nonunion firms gained market edge through lower labor costs.[^7]

But here is the crucial corrective from the EPI’s research: at most one-fifth of the decline in union density is attributable to manufacturing’s erosion. Severe declines in union coverage occurred in nonmanufacturing sectors as well — utilities, transportation, construction, mining, and communications.[^6] The primary drivers were legal obstruction, employer aggression, and political choices — not inevitable economic forces.

By 2024, less than 10% of the U.S. workforce had union representation, compared to over 20% in 1983 and 35% at the peak in the 1950s. In the private sector, it was just under 6%.[^8]

-----

## Part III: Amazon as the Modern Factory — and Its War on Organizing

Amazon is now the paradigmatic case of what post-union labor looks like in practice.

### The Injury Data

A December 2024 Senate HELP Committee report found Amazon warehouses recorded 31% more injuries than the industry average. Over the past seven years, Amazon workers were nearly twice as likely to be injured as those at competing warehouses.[^9] A May 2025 analysis found Amazon’s injury rate was still more than 80% higher than the company’s own target, and the serious injury rate was nearly double that of non-Amazon warehouses.[^9]

### The Union Fight

On April 1, 2022, workers at the JFK8 warehouse in Staten Island voted to form the first NLRB-recognized Amazon union in the United States.[^10] It was a genuine grassroots campaign organized by Chris Smalls and Derrick Palmer after Amazon fired Smalls for organizing a COVID walkout. In June 2024, the union affiliated with the Teamsters.[^10]

But Amazon’s response has been a masterclass in legal obstruction. Amazon spent more than $14 million on anti-union consultants in 2022 alone.[^8] Over four years, the NLRB repeatedly found that Amazon illegally and willfully ignored the union’s legitimacy while attempting to coerce workers into ending their organizing efforts.[^11] It took until April 2026 — four full years after the election — for the NLRB to issue a bargaining order forcing Amazon to recognize the union, making JFK8 Teamsters the first to win such an order against the company.[^11]

Meanwhile, union drives at other warehouses have largely failed. A decisive 2,447–829 vote against unionizing occurred at the Garner, North Carolina, facility in early 2025.[^8] Amazon’s strategy works precisely because the legal framework allows it: delay indefinitely, spend limitlessly on anti-union consultants, retaliate and settle later for trivial penalties.

-----

## Part IV: AI and Algorithmic Management — The New Boss

This is where the story turns genuinely novel. AI is not just replacing workers — it is replacing *the conditions under which organizing was historically possible.*

### Robots as Pace-Setters, Not Replacements

Amazon’s robotic fulfillment centers had a serious injury rate of 7.9 per 100 workers in 2019, more than 54% higher than non-robotic facilities. The reason: robots set the pace, and management monitors workers’ speed in real time, logging any lag as “time off task.”[^9] The robots don’t eliminate jobs immediately — they intensify the remaining jobs and make the human body a bottleneck in a machine system.

### The Automation Trajectory

In 2025, Amazon disclosed that it had a million robots operating at its warehouses — nearly as many as its approximately 1.5 million human workers.[^12] Leaked internal documents show the company plans to automate 75% of its entire operations, with a strategy to avoid hiring 160,000+ people by 2027 and cut roughly 600,000 hires over the next several years.[^13] The leaked documents also suggest avoiding terms like “automation” and “AI” when discussing robotics.[^13] That last detail is telling — even Amazon knows the optics are bad.

### Algorithmic Management as Union Suppression

This is the deepest structural issue. The United Nations University and UC Berkeley Labor Center have both documented how AI-driven management systems fragment work, atomize workers, and eliminate the stable, communal work relationships that historically enabled organizing. Remote and gig-based work models, facilitated by AI, create a fragmented workforce, making it more difficult for trade unions to connect with potential members.[^14] When your supervisor is an algorithm tracking your “time off task” in real-time, there is no supervisor to persuade, no foreman to negotiate with. The locus of power becomes invisible and distributed.

UC Berkeley’s Labor Center analysis of union AI statements found that labor organizations are pushing for “algorithmic guidance” rather than “algorithmic management” — insisting workers must retain authority to override or modify algorithmic directives rather than serve as rubber stamps or liability shields for automated systems.[^15]

-----

## Part V: Trajectory — What Comes Next

The historical pattern suggests three possible futures, and they are not mutually exclusive:

### 1. The *Jacobin* Thesis — No Apocalypse, Just Degradation

*Jacobin*‘s analysis argues the near future of “efficiency gains” will be much like the recent past: increased surveillance, discipline, and gigification combined with displacement of labor through robotics improvements that are mostly masked through company growth.[^16] Under this model, Amazon doesn’t fire a million people overnight. It simply stops hiring as many, chews through the current workforce faster, and slowly replaces functions — all while maintaining plausible deniability.

### 2. The Middle Management Surprise

Amazon laid off roughly 14,000 corporate jobs in late 2025, signaling that AI may actually hit white-collar coordination and decision-making roles before it fully displaces manual warehouse labor.[^17] The irony is sharp: the people who designed the surveillance systems may get automated before the people being surveilled.

### 3. A New Organizing Model

Gallup polls show 70% of the U.S. public and almost 90% of young workers approve of unions — a figure not seen since the mid-1960s.[^18] Public sentiment is massively pro-union even as actual membership is at historic lows. The Teamsters’ escalation at Amazon — striking more than 200 Amazon facilities in over 20 states during the 2024 holiday season[^19] — and the April 2026 bargaining order represent real strategic developments. And unions are beginning to bargain directly over AI deployment. Workers are using union bargaining power to negotiate provisions that prevent job elimination, limit surveillance and algorithmic management, and enable workers to benefit from productivity gains.[^20]

-----

## The Structural Problem

The deeper issue, and this is where the historical analysis really bites: the NLRA’s original architecture — organizing workplace by workplace through elections — was always vulnerable to employers who could outspend, outlast, and outmaneuver individual campaigns. The system of workplace elections meant that unions had to organize each new factory or firm individually rather than organize by industry.[^4] Amazon exploits this flaw perfectly. It can fight each warehouse individually, spend millions per campaign, and delay for years even after losing.

AI compounds this vulnerability in a way that is historically unprecedented. Previous waves of technology — the assembly line, containerization, computing — changed *what* work was done. Algorithmic management changes *who is in charge of the work itself.* When management decisions are encoded in software, there is no individual manager making a choice that can be grieved, challenged, or negotiated. The boss becomes code. And you can’t organize against code using the legal frameworks designed for human bosses in 1935.

The trajectory, if stated directly, points toward a period that most resembles the pre-New Deal era — where worker power depends not on legal frameworks that protect it, but on the raw capacity of workers to make production stop. The Teamsters understand this, which is why they’ve gone straight to strikes rather than waiting for the legal process to deliver. Whether that strategy can scale faster than Amazon can automate is the defining labor question of the next decade.

